Constraints on the star formation histories of galaxies in the Local Cosmological Volume

P Kroupa, M Haslbauer, I Banik, S T Nagesh, J Pflamm-Altenburg
Author Notes
Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society, Volume 497, Issue 1, September 2020, Pages 37–43, https://doi.org/10.1093/mnras/staa1851
Published:
22 July 2020
Article history
  • PDF
  • Split View
  • Cite
  • Permissions Icon Permissions
  • Share

ABSTRACT

The majority of galaxies with current star formation rates (SFRs), SFRo≥10−3M⊙yr−1SFRo≥10−3M⊙yr−1⁠, in the Local Cosmological Volume, where observations should be reliable, have the property that their observed SFRo is larger than their average SFR. This is in tension with the evolution of galaxies described by delayed-τ models, according to which the opposite would be expected. The tension is apparent in that local galaxies imply the star formation time-scale τ ≈ 6.7 Gyr, much longer than the 3.5–4.5 Gyr obtained using an empirically determined main sequence at several redshifts. Using models where the SFR is a power law in time of the form ∝(t − t1)η for t1 = 1.8 Gyr (with no stars forming prior to t1) implies that η = 0.18 ± 0.03. This suggested near-constancy of a galaxy’s SFR over time raises non-trivial problems for the evolution and formation time of galaxies, but is broadly consistent with the observed decreasing main sequence with increasing age of the Universe.

1 INTRODUCTION

The formation and evolution of observed galaxies constitutes a cosmological boundary condition that must be fulfilled by any physically realistic theory of cosmological structure formation and evolution. A Milky Way (MW)-type galaxy is generally thought to have begun forming ≈12 Gyr ago (i.e. at time t1 ≈ 1.8 Gyr after the big bang, Planck Collaboration XIII 2016), reaching a maximum star formation rate (SFR)1 with the SFR subsequently decreasing (e.g. Mor et al. 2019).

The MW is a well-studied case, for which measurements of the phase-space, chemical, and age parameters of a large ensemble of disc stars reveal a complex star formation history (SFH). It decreases from SFR≈10−20M⊙SFR≈10−20M⊙ yr−1 about 10 Gyr ago to a minimum with SFR≈2.7M⊙SFR≈2.7M⊙ yr−1 about 66 Gyr ago, reaching a local maximum of SFR≈8M⊙SFR≈8M⊙ yr−1 about 3.53.5 Gyr ago and decreasing to a present-day value of SFRo≈1.3M⊙SFRo≈1.3M⊙ yr−1 (Mor et al. 2019). While the data may also be interpreted with a constant SFR≈4M⊙SFR≈4M⊙ yr−1 over the past ≈12≈12 Gyr (yielding a present-day disc stellar mass of M∗≈4.8×1010M⊙M∗≈4.8×1010M⊙⁠), a general trend of a decreasing SFR has also been found by Zonoozi, Mahani & Kroupa (2019) based on the shape of the galaxy-wide stellar mass function, and from an analysis of the kinematical imprint of star formation in a clustered mode according to which the thick disc may have been formed from an elevated SFR about 10–12 Gyr ago (Kroupa 2002). Ruiz-Lara et al. (2020) map the SFH from >12 Gyr ago until today, finding consistency with the analysis by Mor et al. (2019) and showing time-resolved evidence that it may have been modulated over the past 6 Gyr by the orbit of the Sagittarius satellite galaxy.2 In the context of Milgromian Dynamics (MOND; Milgrom 1983; Bekenstein & Milgrom 1984), the SFH of the MW is likely to have been significantly affected by its encounter with Andromeda (M31) about 7–10 Gyr ago (Zhao et al. 2013).3 The MW SFH is thus not likely that of an unperturbed self-regulated secularly evolving disc galaxy. The other large galaxy in the Local Group, M31, had SFR≈5M⊙SFR≈5M⊙ yr−1 from 14 to 8 Gyr ago, with a dip to SFR≈1M⊙SFR≈1M⊙ yr−1 about 8–6 Gyr ago, a maximum near 5M⊙5M⊙ yr−1 about 5–1.5 Gyr ago and a decline to SFRo≈0.1M⊙SFRo≈0.1M⊙ yr−1 or less (Williams et al. 2017, the quoted values comprise only the region of M31 mapped by the PHAT survey). It appears that the SFHs of the MW and M31 may be correlated, as the initial larger values, the minima and maxima appear to be broadly in-phase.

On the other hand, the Triangulum galaxy (M33) is a near-flocculent disc galaxy in the Local Group without a significant bulge and appears to have evolved largely without significant perturbations. Its SFR has increased significantly until the present time, with SFRo≈0.5M⊙SFRo≈0.5M⊙ yr−1, while about 10 Gyr ago, SFR≈0.04M⊙SFR≈0.04M⊙ yr−1 with evidence for an acceleration and then minimum about 5 Gyr ago (Javadi et al. 2017). This SFH may be related to its orbit around M31 (Patel, Besla & Sohn 2017). The Large Magellanic Cloud (LMC) also shows an increasing SFR until today with a dip about 5 Gyr ago (Meschin et al. 2014). This SFH cannot be representative of an isolated self-regulated disc galaxy because the LMC is strongly interacting with the Small Magellanic Cloud and also with the MW. It may be noteworthy that all four major galaxies of the Local Group discussed above share a similar depression in their SFHs roughly 55 Gyr ago. The evidence from the larger galaxies in the Local Group concerning the shapes of their SFHs is thus somewhat ambiguous and is mired by the Local Group members being subject to relatively strong encounters. The rather strikingly symmetrical arrangement of matter within the Local Group appears to be additionally troubling (Pawlowski et al. 2013).

In order to improve our understanding of the formation and evolution of galaxies, larger and representative samples are needed. Delgado-Serrano et al. (2010) used Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS) data to show that the vast majority of galaxies with stellar masses M∗>1.5×1010M⊙M∗>1.5×1010M⊙ are star-forming disc galaxies in the Local Universe as well as 66 Gyr ago, with elliptical galaxies comprising an unchanging 3−4 per cent3−4 per cent of the studied ensembles. The observational study by De Propris et al. (2014) of merger rates using close pairs indicates blue galaxies to have a small merger incidence, less than that expected in standard cosmology. De Propris et al. (2014) find ‘Galaxies in these close pairs are likely to have undergone a series of previous encounters and close passes’ which poses a problem for the expected rapid merging due to dynamical friction on the large and massive dark matter haloes (Kroupa 2015; Oehm, Thies & Kroupa 2017). De Propris et al. (2014) conclude ‘At face value our findings minimize the importance of major mergers and interactions for galaxy evolution and argue that most galaxy evolution takes place via internal and secular processes.’ Based on a survey of major disc galaxies within a distance of ≈8 Mpc, Kormendy et al. (2010) find about half of the sample of 19 massive disc galaxies have no evidence for a classical bulge, raising the question ‘How can hierarchical clustering make so many giant, pure-disc galaxies with no evidence for merger-built bulges?’ Comparing models of hierarchical galaxy formation with SDSS data, Shankar et al. (2014) conclude ‘Despite the observational uncertainties, the data tend to disfavour hierarchical models characterized by strong and impulsive disc instabilities, strong gas dissipation in major mergers, short dynamical friction time-scales.’ In "The Impossibly Early Galaxy Problem", (Steinhardt et al. 2016) 1012−13M⊙1012−13M⊙ dark matter halos to be overabundant at z = 6 − 8 than expected if hierarchical assembly through mergers were to be valid. Mergers may thus be playing a lesser role in galaxy evolution than currently thought. The vastly dominating class of disc galaxies may thus be simpler than thought. Indeed, a principal component analysis of the galaxies selected with 21 cm-observations implies star-forming galaxies are governed by one parameter only, making such galaxies simpler than expected (Disney et al. 2008). Disc galaxies are well-known to obey well-defined Milgromian laws (Milgrom 1983; Bekenstein & Milgrom 1984), such as the baryonic Tully–Fisher relation (McGaugh 2012) and the radial–acceleration relation (Lelli et al. 2017; for a review, see Famaey & McGaugh 2012).

In view of this documented simplicity of galaxies, it is also important to quantify if the SFHs typically increase or decrease with time, because this question is intimately linked to the cosmological matter cycle and budget. By compiling many different surveys of star-forming galaxies with M∗>109M⊙M∗>109M⊙⁠, Speagle et al. (2014, hereafter SP14) found them to form a well-defined tight SFR versus M* correlation, which is known as the main sequence of galaxies (e.g. Davé 2008; Renzini & Peng 2015; Popesso et al. 2019). With increasing cosmological redshift z, the main sequence evolves to larger SFR for a given M*. The tight correlation of the main sequence across cosmic time and the apparent simplicity of galaxies can be distilled into the understanding that while simple, galaxies tend to evolve according to ‘delayed-τ’ models. After first increasing from an age, t, of the Universe of about t=3t=3 Gyr (⁠10.810.8 Gyr ago), after t≈6.5−7.5t≈6.5−7.5 Gyr their SFRs decrease as their gas is consumed through star formation (fig. 10 in SP14).4 These studies suggest that the SFHs of galaxies can be described by the delayed-τ model (equation 4) and consequently that the present-day SFR of a typical galaxy,5 SFRo, needs to be smaller than the average value SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯SFR¯⁠, i.e.
SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯SFRo>1.SFR¯SFRo>1.
(1)
Davé (2008) suggests this to be broadly consistent with dark-matter-based hydrodynamical simulations. Galaxy-formation simulations in Milgromian gravitation based on single-cloud collapse with negligible further gas accretion also lead to such a general behaviour, albeit with a much larger SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯/SFRoSFR¯/SFRo (Wittenburg, Kroupa & Famaey 2020).

In order to improve knowledge of galaxy formation and evolution, it is useful to also consider the ensemble of galaxies in the nearby Universe. Peebles & Nusser (2010) compare structure formation models to the spatial distribution of galaxies in the Local Cosmological Volume, defined by the sphere with radius 88Mpc, finding significant tension between the predicted and observed distribution of major galaxies. Here, the Catalogue of Neighbouring Galaxies (Section 2) is used to address if SFRo<SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯SFRo<SFR¯⁠. In Section 3, it is shown that galaxies in the Local Cosmological Volume pose a challenge to this generally accepted understanding. Section 4 presents a discussion and the conclusions.

2 THE GALAXIES IN THE LOCAL COSMOLOGICAL VOLUME

The Catalogue of Neighbouring Galaxies (Karachentsev et al. 2004) and its update (Karachentsev, Makarov & Kaisina 2013) are used to extract the K-band luminosities and the SFRs based on integrated H α and far-ultraviolet (FUV) measurements for galaxies within a distance of ≈11 Mpc. The catalogue also lists limit flags on the FUV- and Hα-based SFR values. If a SFR value is marked with such a flag, it is excluded from the here presented analysis (but including flagged SFR values do not significantly affect the results). This gives a sample of 870 galaxies, from 1145. From these 870 galaxies, 267 have only far-ultraviolet (FUV)-based SFR values, 128 have only Hα based SFRs, and 475 have both measurements available. Thus, 14.7 per cent14.7 per cent and 30.7 per cent30.7 per cent galaxies lack FUV- and H α-based SFR measurements, respectively.6 The K-band luminosity values are converted to M* using a mass-to-light ratio of 0.6 (Lelli, McGaugh & Schombert 2016).

For galaxies which have both SFR measurements available, SFRo = (SFRFUV + SFRH α)/2 is adopted. Their SFRs based on integrated H α and FUV measurements are depicted in Fig. 1. The condition SFRo≥10−3M⊙SFRo≥10−3M⊙ yr−1 leaves 386 galaxies. For the galaxies which only have the FUV- or H α-based values, SFRo = SFRFUV or SFRo = SFRH α, respectively (these galaxies do not appear in Fig. 1). Applying the cut SFRo≥10−3M⊙SFRo≥10−3M⊙ yr−1 leaves 109 and 88 galaxies that have only SFRFUV or SFRH α data, respectively.

Figure 1.
Open in new tabDownload slide

Comparison of the FUV- and H α-based SFRo values for those 386 galaxies in the Catalogue of Neighbouring Galaxies (Section 2) which have both measurements (and no limit flag on the SFR measurements) and for which also SFRo=(SFRFUV+SFRHα)/2≥10−3M⊙SFRo=(SFRFUV+SFRHα)/2≥10−3M⊙ yr−1. The red dashed line is the 1:1 relation. The Catalogue of Neighbouring Galaxies does not provide uncertainties, but from the distance uncertainties (Karachentsev et al. 2004, 2013) it may be assumed that each measurement plotted here has a representative uncertainty of 30 per cent (not shown). Throughout the present analysis, the data are therefore treated with equal weights.

Galaxies with SFRo<10−3M⊙SFRo<10−3M⊙ yr−1 are not considered in the present analysis for the following four reasons (Karachentsev & Kaisina 2013 provide an in-depth discussion of these issues):

  1. The SFRo values may be affected by a pronounced top-light galaxy-wide initial mass function (gwIMF) such that SFRo,H α < SFRo,FUV. Pflamm-Altenburg, Weidner & Kroupa (2009), Pflamm-Altenburg & Kroupa (2009), and section 4.3 in Jeřábková et al. (2018) provide a detailed discussion of this gwIMF behaviour, with the resolved dwarf galaxy DDO 154, which has a corresponding lack of massive stars, being a case in point (Watts et al. 2018). Indeed, the ratio SFRo,H α/SFRo,FUV is measured to decrease with decreasing SFRo,FUV or SFRo,H α (Lee et al. 2009), as predicted via the IGIMF theory7 if the gwIMF becomes increasingly top-light with decreasing SFR (Pflamm-Altenburg et al. 2009), a trend observationally also suggested for more massive disc galaxies (Gunawardhana et al. 2011). This behaviour of the gwIMF with SFR would imply dwarf galaxies to be as efficient in forming stars as major disc galaxies (all having a gas depletion or consumption time-scale of about 3 Gyr), therewith explaining their ability to form their observed stellar populations within a Hubble time without the need to postulate that they have had much higher SFRs in the past (Pflamm-Altenburg et al. 2009). Also noteworthy in this context is that two well-studied galaxies, the ultra-diffuse Dragonfly 44 and the ultra-faint satellite Boötes I, had the same gas-depletion time as the above-mentioned star-forming dwarf galaxies as long as the analysis is performed self-consistently within the IGIMF theory (Haghi et al. 2019; Yan, Jerabkova & Kroupa 2020).

  2. Related to the systematically changing gwIMF just discussed, it has been customary to describe star formation throughout a galaxy as being stochastic, an approach discussed in detail in Elmegreen (1997) and Elmegreen (1999).8 Dwarf galaxies with low SFRs may lead to an undersampling of the gwIMF, but only if a central tenet of the IGIMF theory is adopted, namely that stars form in embedded clusters that dictate the available mass for the stellar population per cluster, leading to a difference in various SFR tracers (da Silva, Fumagalli & Krumholz 2014). Related to the suggestion that star formation is stochastic, Kennicutt & Evans (2012) discuss the possibility that dwarf galaxies may be prone to temporal variations of their SFRs. Applebaum et al. (2020) study the effect of a stochastic gwIMF on the formation and evolution of dwarf galaxies with cosmological simulations.

  3. It is possible that the measured H α and UV fluxes are affected by photon leakage, dust obscuration, and redenning and other physical effects (Calzetti 2008, 2013). It is likely that these are relevant, but the authors of the research papers reporting evidence for systematic variations of the gwIMF in galaxies correct for these biases (Hoversten & Glazebrook 2008; Lee et al. 2009; Gunawardhana et al. 2011).

  4. Many of the least massive galaxies in the Local Cosmological Volume with M∗<107M⊙M∗<107M⊙ are satellite galaxies that stopped forming stars many Gyr ago (e.g. Grebel 1997; Grebel, Gallagher & Harbeck 2003). Dwarf galaxies sufficiently far from major galaxies of this mass behave as disc galaxies (e.g. the dwarf galaxy DDO 210 which is barely more massive than a massive globular cluster and which has a Milgromian rotation curve, putting it on the baryonic Tully–Fisher relation; Famaey & McGaugh 2012). Meanwhile, dwarf galaxies within the vicinity of major galaxies have lost their gas (Grebel et al. 2003).

Overall, dwarf and major star-forming galaxies thus appear to conform to the same basic physical evolution, although differences between the SFHs at the lowest mass end are evident and remain to be understood (Albers et al. 2019). Galaxies with SFRo<10−3M⊙SFRo<10−3M⊙ yr−1 are therefore considered to have too insecure SFRs and are thus omitted from the present analysis. For the in-total 583 galaxies used in this analysis, the gwIMF is near to canonical (Gunawardhana et al. 2011; Jeřábková et al. 2018).

In a companion paper (Haslbauer et al. in preparation), the Catalogue of Neighbouring Galaxies is compared with the SP14 main sequence. The (SFRo, M*) values are in excellent agreement at M∗>109M⊙M∗>109M⊙⁠, showing that the Catalogue of Neighbouring Galaxies conforms to the compilation by SP14.

3 THE CURRENT VERSUS THE AVERAGE SFR

3.1 Theoretical expectations

Assume a galaxy forms stars from time t1 until time t2, the latter being the present day if the galaxy is still forming stars. The SFH can be written as SFR(t)=SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯+ΔSFR(t)SFR(t)=SFR¯+ΔSFR(t) such that the average SFR of any galaxy over the time scale tsf ≡ t2 − t1 becomes

with temporal deviations from SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯SFR¯ satisfying,

(3)
This implies that if SFRo=SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯SFRo=SFR¯⁠, any decreasing SFH must have had a compensating increase.

SFRdel(t>t1)=Adelτ2(t−t1)exp(−t−t1τ),SFRdel(t>t1)=Adelτ2(t−t1)exp⁡(−t−t1τ),

The observationally constrained galaxy main-sequence evolution analysed by SP14 suggests that the typical real star-forming galaxy undergoes an evolution beginning at t1≈3t1≈3 Gyr and with SFRdel,max/SFRo,del > 2. The maximum value of the SFR, SFRdel,max, is reached when t − t1 = τ at the time 6.5 < t/Gyr < 7.5 (fig. 10 in SP14) such that 3.5 < τ/Gyr < 4.5. Since tsf≈12tsf≈12 Gyr for the galaxies observed in the Local Group, these galaxies would be in the 2.7 < x < 3.4 phase of their evolution, i.e. in the falling part of their SFH. If the nearby galaxies concur to this evolution, then according to Fig. 2 they ought to have
1.5<SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯SFRo<2.3.1.5<SFR¯SFRo<2.3.

3.2 The Local Volume

The sample of Neighbouring Galaxies (Section 2) can be used to assess the ratio SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯/SFRoSFR¯/SFRo because these galaxies have well-measured M* and SFRo values. The present-day stellar mass of the galaxy defines the average SFR,
SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯≡ζM∗tsf,SFR¯≡ζM∗tsf,
(10)
where ζ accommodates mass-loss through stellar evolution (ζ ≈ 1.3 according to a canonical single-burst stellar population, as evident in fig. 1 of Baumgardt & Makino 2003). Note that 1 < ζ < 1.3 for a galaxy with a constant SFR and a canonical gwIMF, but ζ also depends on the gwIMF and can reach values as large as 2–3 for extreme star-bursting, low-metallicity galaxies (according to the IGIMF theory, see e.g. Yan, Jerabkova & Kroupa 2017; Dabringhausen 2019; Yan et al. 2019). According to the IGIMF theory, the nearby galaxies used here are expected to have 1.0 < ζ < 1.3. By adopting ζ = 1.3, we are thus working conservatively − the expected smaller value would bring a larger conflict with the delayed-τ SFHs (see below).

Both observationally derived values, SFRo and SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯SFR¯⁠, are compared in Fig. 3 for the galaxies with SFRo≥10−3M⊙SFRo≥10−3M⊙ yr−1. Fig. 4 plots the empirical SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯/SFRoSFR¯/SFRo ratios to test if equation (1) or (9) can be fulfilled by the data. It is apparent that the delayed-τ SFH description cannot account for the data if tsf=12tsf=12 Gyr and τ ≈ 4 Gyr. Reducing tsf to 6 Gyr would allow the model to account for the data, but such short tsf violates the observed ages of galactic discs, which suggest tsf≈12tsf≈12 Gyr (e.g. Knox, Hawkins & Hambly 1999).

There is a clear preference for (SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯/SFRo)clip<1(SFR¯/SFRo)clip<1⁠, though given the possibility of systematics (e.g. in the mass-to-light ratio), (SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯/SFRo)clip=1(SFR¯/SFRo)clip=1 is possible, in which case x = 1.79 and τ=6.7τ=6.7 Gyr, assuming tsf=12tsf=12 Gyr. But the data certainly argue against (SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯/SFRo)clip>1(SFR¯/SFRo)clip>1⁠.

3.3 A power-law SFH?

Which type of SFH might account for the observational data and in particular for the mean value of (SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯/SFRo)clip=0.85(SFR¯/SFRo)clip=0.85⁠, or at least get the ratio down to 1? As an ansatz,
SFRincr(t>t1)=Aincr(t−t1)η,SFRincr(t>t1)=Aincr(t−t1)η,
(12)
with SFRincr(t≤t1)=0M⊙SFRincr(t≤t1)=0M⊙ yr−1 as before, η ≠ −1 being the power-law index and Aincr the normalization.
The present-day average and present-day SFR are, respectively,
SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯incr=Aincr1+ηtηsf,SFR¯incr=Aincr1+ηtsfη,
(13)
SFRo,incr=Aincrtηsf.SFRo,incr=Aincrtsfη.
(14)
To get the correct total normalization M* at the present time,
Aincr=ζ(1+η)M∗/t1+ηsf.Aincr=ζ(1+η)M∗/tsf1+η.
(15)
Thus,
SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯incrSFRo,incr=11+η≤1.SFR¯incrSFRo,incr=11+η≤1.
(16)
The uncertainty of η is
ση=η−−η+2,whereση=η−−η+2,where
(17)
η±=10.85×10±0.011−1.η±=10.85×10±0.011−1.
(18)
The mean value of (SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯/SFRo)clip=0.85±0.02(SFR¯/SFRo)clip=0.85±0.02 (Section 3.2), implying that η = 0.18 ± 0.03. The true uncertainty is probably at least about 30 per cent larger since the value quoted here treats all data points with equal weight and ignores the observational uncertainties that are not provided by Karachentsev et al. (2004, 2013). Note that SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯incr/SFRo,incr=1SFR¯incr/SFRo,incr=1 can be recovered for the case η = 0, which implies that any individual galaxy has the same SFR at all times.
According to this model, the stellar mass growth of an isolated non-interacting galaxy would be
M∗(t−t1)=1ζ(1+η)(t−t1)SFR(t−t1).M∗(t−t1)=1ζ(1+η)(t−t1)SFR(t−t1).
(19)
For the case η = 0, M*∝(t − t1). Since the cosmic scale factor , this model would be very similar to the case M*∝a at late times, where the observational constraints are strongest.
Assuming all galaxies begin forming stars at the same t1, the main sequence would thus evolve according to
SFR(t−t1)=ζ(1+η)M∗(t−t1)t−t1.SFR(t−t1)=ζ(1+η)M∗(t−t1)t−t1.
(20)
At a given M*, the SFR would decrease with an increasing age of the Universe, t, because a galaxy with fixed M* needed a larger SFR to reach this mass in a shorter time when the Universe was younger.

As a quantitative example, consider galaxies with a fixed M∗=1010M⊙M∗=1010M⊙ at different times in standard cosmology. Suppose these all started forming stars at t1 = 1.8 Gyr (i.e. about 1212 Gyr ago) according to ζ = 1.3, η = 0. At t = 2.1 Gyr, z ≈ 3 such that SFR(0.3Gyr)=43M⊙SFR(0.3Gyr)=43M⊙ yr−1. At t=6t=6 Gyr, z ≈ 1, and SFR=3.1M⊙SFR=3.1M⊙ yr−1. These are broadly consistent with the evolution documented by SP14, namely that SFR≈32+24−18M⊙SFR≈32−18+24M⊙ yr−1 at z = 3 and SFR≈10+7.8−5.6M⊙SFR≈10−5.6+7.8M⊙ yr−1 at z = 1 (their fig. 8).

The specific SFR becomes
sSFR(t−t1)=ζ(1+η)1t−t1,sSFR(t−t1)=ζ(1+η)1t−t1,
(21)
such that today (⁠t−t1=tsf=12t−t1=tsf=12 Gyr and with ζ = 1.3, η = 0),
sSFR(t−t1)=1.1×10−10yr−1.sSFR(t−t1)=1.1×10−10yr−1.
(22)
As a further consistency check, in the regime where the gwIMF is expected to be comparable to the canonical IMF (i.e. ζ ≈ 1.3) and thus for M∗=1010M⊙M∗=1010M⊙⁠, the observational study by Ilbert et al. (2015) leads to sSFR=1.23×10−10sSFR=1.23×10−10 yr−1 (their equation 1 with z = 0), being in reasonable agreement with equation (22). Note that the sSFR versus M* relation might not be constant as its slope would be given by the value ζ(SFRo, Z) if the gwIMF depends on the SFR and metallicity, Z. According to the IGIMF theory, ζ > 1.3 for galaxies with SFRo>10M⊙SFRo>10M⊙ yr−1 (cf. Gunawardhana et al. 2011; Yan et al. 2017). The slope of the sSFR versus M* relation thus encodes the systematic variation of the gwIMF.

4 DISCUSSION AND CONCLUSION

The Catalogue of Neighbouring Galaxies (Section 2) provides a sample of star-forming galaxies that are used here to test a robust expectation concerning galactic SFHs (equations 1 and 9). This expectation comes from the general understanding that galaxies typically have decreasing SFRs now, and should thus have an average SFR exceeding the present value (⁠SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯/SFRo>1SFR¯/SFRo>1⁠). Within the context of the delayed-τ models (Section 3.1), the present results are indicative of a rather long star formation time-scale of τ ≈ 6.7 Gyr, much longer than the 3.5–4.5 Gyr estimated by SP14. The tension between their results and the local sample is also evident in Figs 3 and 5, which show that for the plausible assumption that galaxies have been forming stars for 12 Gyr, the average and present SFRs are nearly the same. However, SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯/SFRo≈2SFR¯/SFRo≈2 is expected (Fig. 2).

The nearby galaxies with SFRo≥10−3M⊙SFRo≥10−3M⊙ yr−1 are in tension with this expectation by having present-day SFRs which are larger than the average values as estimated from the observationally constrained masses in stars. The data are consistent with galaxies having a constant SFH (η = 0 in equation 12). While the mass of an individual galaxy increases with time, for a given fixed stellar mass, the SFR would decrease with time (equation 20). This is broadly consistent with the results obtained by SP14. The slope of the sSFR versus M* relation reflects the systematically varying gwIMF.

A caveat of these deductions is that the data in the Catalogue of Neighbouring Galaxies may be systematically biased, for example if the measured SFRs are too large or the observationally derived stellar masses are too low. However, the bias would need to be a factor of ≈1.2 in SFRo or in M* (in this case the K-band mass-to-light ratio would be 0.72 rather than 0.6 as used in Section 2) to shift SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯/SFRoSFR¯/SFRo to the regime >1 (Section 3). While this could occur, a much larger bias would be required to get the expected ratio of SFR¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯/SFRo≈2SFR¯/SFRo≈2 (Section 3.1). This appears implausible given that these galaxies comprise the nearby sample, which ought to be well observed. Furthermore, the SFRo and M* values are consistent with the redshift z = 0 main sequence as determined by SP14 and shown explicitly in Haslbauer et al. (in preparation).

It may also be possible that the Local Cosmological Volume, by being part of a 400 Mpc underdensity (Karachentsev 2012; Keenan, Barger & Cowie 2013), is not entirely representative and that the galaxies it contains lag in their evolution compared to galaxies further away, which are used by SP14 to quantify the evolution of the main sequence. The star-by-star data of the Local Group galaxies and their globular clusters (Grebel 1997) do not, however, support the notion that the Local Cosmological Volume contains younger galaxies than the cosmological average.

If the tension between the Neighbouring Galaxies and the evolution of the galactic SFHs (fig. 10 in SP14) remains, then this may be indicative of an issue with calculating the rest-frame physical properties of galaxies at z > 0 and thus with the cosmological model employed for this calculation (cf. Balakrishna Subramani et al. 2019). It may be worth exploring which cosmological model might ease the tension, but this is beyond the scope of the present contribution.

Assuming that the data in the Local Cosmological Volume used here are robust and unbiased, then they would possibly suggest a roughly constant or slightly increasing SFR in a typical galaxy over time. The flocculent disc galaxy Triangulum indeed suggests an increasing SFR. The physical origin of this dependence of the SFR on time and present-day mass of the galaxy (equation 12) remain to be explored in this eventuality.
